05907nam a22008175i 9783110643497DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106434977 a10.1515/97831106434972doi  a(DE-B1597)530706  a(OCoLC)1149448806  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0061002bisacsh1 aChilders, Jeff W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDivining Gospel :bOracles of Interpretation in a Syriac Manuscript of John /cJeff W. Childers. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XI, 230 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aManuscripta Biblica ;v400tFrontmatter -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- tContents -- t1. Opening the Gospel -- t2. Divination in Late Antique Christian Practice -- t3. Divining Gospels: A Suppressed and Neglected Genre -- t4. “Fearsome and Terrible Word of God:” A Closer Look at the Form and History of The Syriac Codex -- t5. “You Will Find What You Seek:” The Divinatory Material of the Syriac Codex -- t6. Interpreting Hermeneia: The Use and Function of the Divining Gospel -- t7. Oracles of Biblical Interpretation: Examining the Relationship between Divination, John’s Gospel, and the User -- t8. The Demise of the Divining Gospel -- tBibliography -- tAppendix: Syriac Words in the Puššāqē -- tIndices0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAncient manuscripts of John’s Gospel containing hermeneiai have long puzzled scholars, provoking debate about their origins, purpose, and use. The fragmentary nature of the early evidence has impeded progress towards a better understanding of these specialized books. The present study shows that these books are "Divining Gospels"—editions of John’s Gospel incorporating lot divination materials for use in fortune-telling. The study centers on material presented here for the first time: the text and translation of a unique sixth-century Syriac manuscript, the earliest and most complete example of a hermeneia Gospel. An analysis of the Syriac along with evidence from Greek, Coptic, Latin, and Armenian versions show they all preserve vestiges of the same apparatus, disseminated widely at an early time throughout many different Christian communities. These books must be situated squarely within the development of divinatory practices in early and late antique Christianity. However, they represent a true hermeneutic, a method by which interpreters brought the potency of the Bible to bear on the everyday concerns of people who consulted them for help. Furthermore, the Divining Gospel draws on the special aura that John’s Gospel held in the Christian imagination, both as text and as textual object. An analysis of the interplay between the biblical text and sacred codex, the oracles, the ritual practitioner, and the client enrich our appreciation of this distinctive hermeneutic. Contextualizing these materials in popular use illuminates the fraught relationships between the ecclesial establishment, ritual experts operating on the margins of orthodox respectability, and lay clients seeking knowledge and help.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh  aGospels.  adivination.  ahermeneia.  anew philology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package 2020z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter